@startuml fig-content-type-vs-encoding
skinparam backgroundColor white
skinparam defaultFontName Arial
skinparam defaultFontSize 11
skinparam shadowing false
skinparam sequenceMessageAlign center

title Content-Type vs Content-Encoding in HTTP

participant "Client\n(browser / curl)" as C #FFE0B2
participant "Server\n(HTTP origin)" as S #C8E6C9

C -> S : GET /data.json\nAccept: application/json\nAccept-Encoding: gzip

S --> C : 200 OK\nContent-Type: application/json; charset=utf-8\nContent-Encoding: gzip\n\n[gzip-compressed JSON body]

note right of S
  Content-Type = what the data is
  (MIME type + charset)
end note

note right of S
  Content-Encoding = how the data
  is wrapped for transfer (gzip)
end note

note left of C
  The client first decompresses
  (undo Content-Encoding), then
  interprets (use Content-Type).
end note

legend bottom
  Content-Type describes the semantic meaning of the payload.
  Content-Encoding describes the transfer-level transformation.
  The receiver must reverse the encoding before parsing the content type.
endlegend
@enduml
